Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @Potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Pick and finely chop fronds from @Dill{1/4%ounce}.

Trim and discard woody bottom ends from asparagus or cut @Broccoli{12%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. (Save potatoes for another use.)

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} and a pinch of @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until lightly browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Swap in asparagus or broccoli for potatoes; roast asparagus for 10-12 minutes, or broccoli for 12-15 minutes.

While potatoes roast, pat @Chicken Cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%tablespoon} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest.

While chicken cooks, trim @Green Beans{6%ounce} if necessary; toss on a second baking sheet with a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{} and a pinch of @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Roast on middle rack until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Heat pan used for chicken over medium heat. Stir in @Chicken Stock Concentrate{1} and @water{2%tablespoon}, and as much chopped dill and @Dijon Mustard{2%teaspoon} as you like.

Remove pan from heat; stir in @Sour Cream{3%tablespoon} and @Butter{1%tablespoon}, scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, add more water 1 tsp at a time until it reaches a drizzling consistency.

Slice chicken crosswise.

Divide chicken, potatoes, and green beans between plates. Drizzle sauce over chicken. Garnish with any remaining chopped dill and serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165º.